# GitHub CLI (`gh`) preference

When work touches **GitHub** (repos, PRs, issues, releases, Actions, org/repo settings, API calls to `api.github.com`), **prefer the GitHub CLI** over ad-hoc curl, manual dashboard steps, or guessing REST paths—**when `gh` is available and authenticated**.

## Default to `gh` for

- **Repo metadata and edits**: `gh repo view`, `gh repo edit` (description, visibility, topics), clone with `gh repo clone`
- **Pull requests & issues**: `gh pr create`, `gh pr view`, `gh pr merge`, `gh issue list`, `gh issue create`
- **CI/CD**: `gh run list`, `gh run view`, `gh workflow run`, re-run failed jobs
- **Releases & tags**: `gh release create`, `gh release list`
- **Secrets & variables** (where appropriate): `gh secret set`, `gh variable set`
- **Low-level API**: `gh api` / `gh api graphql` instead of hand-built curl (handles auth and pagination patterns)

## Stay on plain `git` for

Local repository mechanics: `commit`, `rebase`, `merge`, `branch`, `status`, `diff`, `log`—unless the task is specifically “create this on GitHub” (then `gh` often complements `git push`).

## Safety and UX notes

- **Visibility and other destructive flags** may require explicit acceptance (e.g. `--accept-visibility-change-consequences`); do not strip safety flags to “make it work.”
- If `gh` is missing or not logged in, say so and use documented alternatives (`git` + browser, or `gh auth login` guidance)—do not assume `gh` in CI unless the environment provides it.

## Verify auth when unsure

```bash
gh auth status
```
